1
00:00:30,560 --> 00:00:31,560
Hello?

2
00:00:42,080 --> 00:00:43,080
Who are you?

3
00:01:28,360 --> 00:01:31,520
- I'm dreaming, right?
- Oh, I hope so lady.

4
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:33,000
I sure hope so.

5
00:01:34,760 --> 00:01:35,880
She's nice.

6
00:01:38,040 --> 00:01:39,120
Hell.

7
00:01:39,720 --> 00:01:40,960
What's up with them?

8
00:01:42,960 --> 00:01:44,440
What are they waiting for?

9
00:01:48,840 --> 00:01:50,240
First man that comes at a new girl

10
00:01:50,320 --> 00:01:53,760
nearly always gets jumped
by the second man.

11
00:01:53,840 --> 00:01:55,000
Is that right?

12
00:02:08,720 --> 00:02:11,160
Here's a promise, boys.

13
00:02:11,240 --> 00:02:15,520
The first of you to come at me
will die like that.

14
00:02:16,840 --> 00:02:19,200
The second will die slow.

15
00:02:24,200 --> 00:02:25,680
So, boys...

16
00:02:29,560 --> 00:02:31,560
who's first?

17
00:02:41,560 --> 00:02:44,760
- Thank you. That was wonderful.
- Yeah. Taxi.

18
00:02:46,280 --> 00:02:49,760
And no case files.
We didn't mention work once.

19
00:02:49,840 --> 00:02:51,840
- There's hope for us yet.
- Yeah.

20
00:02:52,920 --> 00:02:56,840
So, what is this? Our third date?

21
00:02:56,920 --> 00:02:59,080
I believe that's correct.

22
00:02:59,160 --> 00:03:02,520
Three dates and I still
haven't been to your apartment.

23
00:03:02,600 --> 00:03:05,280
What particular room of my apartment
are you interested in?

24
00:03:05,920 --> 00:03:07,680
- I don't know. How's the kitchen?
- Small.

25
00:03:07,760 --> 00:03:09,240
- Living room?
- Dark.

26
00:03:09,320 --> 00:03:11,280
- What about the bedroom?
- The bedroom, I think you'd like.

27
00:03:11,360 --> 00:03:13,240
Yeah? Taxi.

28
00:03:15,120 --> 00:03:17,680
- But not tonight.
- No?

29
00:03:17,760 --> 00:03:21,520
I have to get a good night's sleep.
I start a new job in the morning.

30
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:24,320
A new job? Congratulations.
Since when?

31
00:03:24,400 --> 00:03:26,280
I heard this morning.

32
00:03:26,360 --> 00:03:29,680
I didn't wanna spoil dinner
with a big discussion about it.

33
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:31,480
Why would it spoil dinner?

34
00:03:32,520 --> 00:03:35,080
I'm coming to work at the GCPD.

35
00:03:35,160 --> 00:03:37,080
I'm you're new medical examiner.

36
00:03:37,640 --> 00:03:38,640
You're kidding.

37
00:03:40,360 --> 00:03:43,920
- Wow, that's great.
- Is it?

38
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:47,560
Of course. I mean, I was the one
that suggested you work there.

39
00:03:47,640 --> 00:03:49,760
- Yes, but now it's real.
- So? Good.

40
00:03:50,800 --> 00:03:52,480
We'll see, won't we?

41
00:03:59,920 --> 00:04:01,080
Good night.

42
00:04:15,360 --> 00:04:20,680
Hey. Gennaro Marx, single, 63.
High-school English teacher.

43
00:04:20,760 --> 00:04:23,560
Same exact surgical incisions
as our last victim.

44
00:04:23,640 --> 00:04:25,480
What are the odds
he's got no adrenal glands?

45
00:04:25,560 --> 00:04:27,640
So, what's he doing with them?

46
00:05:41,880 --> 00:05:43,680
Why?

47
00:05:45,680 --> 00:05:47,080
Help.

48
00:05:49,320 --> 00:05:51,000
- What's the matter with you?
- Help me.

49
00:05:51,080 --> 00:05:52,960
Why won't you help me, Gerald?

50
00:05:54,920 --> 00:05:55,920
Help me.

51
00:06:03,280 --> 00:06:05,440
Do you have everything you need,
Master Bruce?

52
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:07,600
Yes.

53
00:06:12,040 --> 00:06:14,240
{\an5}I can still come with you,
if you want me to.

54
00:06:16,600 --> 00:06:17,720
{\an5}No.

55
00:06:20,640 --> 00:06:23,400
{\an5}- It wouldn't be right.
- No, of course.

56
00:06:28,600 --> 00:06:30,040
{\an5}I'll be fine, Alfred.

57
00:06:30,120 --> 00:06:33,200
{\an5}- You don't have to worry.
- Who said I was worried?

58
00:06:33,280 --> 00:06:34,640
{\an5}I'll be back before dark.

59
00:06:36,480 --> 00:06:37,760
{\an5}I've been on this hike before,
you know?

60
00:06:38,880 --> 00:06:40,080
{\an5}Not without your father.

61
00:06:45,400 --> 00:06:46,520
{\an5}Come here.

62
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:49,000
{\an5}He would've approved, you know?

63
00:06:50,840 --> 00:06:53,440
{\an5}Carrying on the tradition like this.

64
00:06:53,520 --> 00:06:55,440
{\an5}My father and I stayed overnight.

65
00:06:55,520 --> 00:06:57,360
{\an5}We woke up early
to watch the sunrise.

66
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:01,160
It's not the same.

67
00:07:01,240 --> 00:07:02,680
{\an5}Well, maybe next year then.

68
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:08,760
Well, off you go then.

69
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:17,920
And then, the worst of it.

70
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:21,960
{\an5}Maroni had me locked inside a sedan
and tried to crush me alive.

71
00:07:22,040 --> 00:07:25,600
{\an5}So, well, you can imagine my concern.

72
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:27,360
{\an5}Maroni's not a man to let things go

73
00:07:27,440 --> 00:07:30,200
{\an5}and I fear he will come
after me in retaliation.

74
00:07:31,200 --> 00:07:33,120
{\an5}Were you planning
to clean up the place?

75
00:07:33,200 --> 00:07:34,200
{\an5}What?

76
00:07:36,600 --> 00:07:39,960
- I can. If you like.
- It needs it.

77
00:07:40,040 --> 00:07:41,120
Is that blood?

78
00:07:43,200 --> 00:07:44,400
Perhaps.

79
00:07:45,560 --> 00:07:47,080
{\an5}But Don Falcone...

80
00:07:47,160 --> 00:07:51,840
{\an5}While you're at it, maybe you could
do something about the design.

81
00:07:51,920 --> 00:07:53,640
{\an5}The design?

82
00:07:53,720 --> 00:07:56,840
{\an5}It reeks of Fish Mooney.

83
00:07:56,920 --> 00:07:58,480
{\an5}What do you think about the lamps?

84
00:08:00,400 --> 00:08:03,440
{\an5}Don Falcone,
maybe you didn't hear me.

85
00:08:03,520 --> 00:08:05,320
{\an5}I need your protection.

86
00:08:05,400 --> 00:08:09,440
{\an5}- Maroni will surely try and kill me.
- Yes

87
00:08:09,520 --> 00:08:11,000
{\an5}the lamps should go.

88
00:08:12,160 --> 00:08:14,360
{\an5}Don Falcone, please.

89
00:08:14,440 --> 00:08:17,320
{\an5}Maroni wants my scalp
and you'd have me redecorate.

90
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:23,040
This nightclub makes a lot of money.

91
00:08:23,120 --> 00:08:27,400
Without money, we lose influence.
Without influence, we lose control.

92
00:08:27,480 --> 00:08:30,320
And without control,
Maroni killing you is no longer

93
00:08:30,400 --> 00:08:33,600
a hypothetical,
it's a foregone conclusion.

94
00:08:33,680 --> 00:08:35,600
That's why I wanna reopen it.

95
00:08:35,680 --> 00:08:37,360
Under your care.

96
00:08:37,440 --> 00:08:39,320
I can have the club?

97
00:08:41,400 --> 00:08:42,960
- It's mine?
- You've earned it.

98
00:08:43,040 --> 00:08:46,680
Your days of sneaking around
spying on Maroni are over.

99
00:08:46,760 --> 00:08:49,600
You're with me now. Publicly.

100
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:54,040
Things are gonna be much different.
So, spruce up the place. Get it open.

101
00:08:54,120 --> 00:08:57,400
As for Maroni, leave him to me.

102
00:08:59,400 --> 00:09:00,400
What do you got?

103
00:09:00,480 --> 00:09:02,400
Yearbook
where the victim taught English.

104
00:09:02,480 --> 00:09:03,760
I'll tell you one thing.

105
00:09:03,840 --> 00:09:06,360
Girls didn't look like this
when I was back in high school.

106
00:09:06,440 --> 00:09:09,360
- Easy.
- I'm just saying.

107
00:09:10,640 --> 00:09:14,680
- Hi, Jim.
- Lee. You remember Harvey, right?

108
00:09:14,760 --> 00:09:17,440
- Hi, Lee.
- Hi.

109
00:09:17,520 --> 00:09:18,520
She's our new ME.

110
00:09:19,760 --> 00:09:21,080
You're joking.

111
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:24,280
- No.
- Oh, good. You've met.

112
00:09:24,360 --> 00:09:26,160
Detective Gordon
and I know each other.

113
00:09:26,240 --> 00:09:29,760
- Oh, right. From Arkham?
- Right. Arkham.

114
00:09:29,840 --> 00:09:32,840
- Welcome aboard.
- Thank you.

115
00:09:32,920 --> 00:09:34,720
You can fill her in
on your cases later.

116
00:09:34,800 --> 00:09:38,560
Dr. Thompkins, will you follow me?
Lots to get you up to speed on.

117
00:09:38,640 --> 00:09:40,560
It was good to see you again,
detective.

118
00:09:40,640 --> 00:09:42,760
It was really good to see you,
doctor.

119
00:09:47,720 --> 00:09:49,840
You have no luck at all.
Do you, brother?

120
00:09:49,920 --> 00:09:51,400
What do you mean?

121
00:09:51,480 --> 00:09:52,560
You find a fine lady

122
00:09:52,640 --> 00:09:55,200
like that and she comes to work
with you in the same building?

123
00:09:56,200 --> 00:09:58,320
- It's a damn shame.
- Why?

124
00:09:58,400 --> 00:10:02,360
Office romance always
ends in tears. Tears.

125
00:10:02,440 --> 00:10:06,360
- It's not gonna be like that.
- Trust me. I know.

126
00:10:11,160 --> 00:10:12,400
There.

127
00:10:12,480 --> 00:10:15,000
Holy Mother Mary.

128
00:10:15,080 --> 00:10:17,280
- You got him?
- Staring right back at me.

129
00:10:17,360 --> 00:10:20,440
That's him. That's him.
That's the guy from the pool.

130
00:10:20,520 --> 00:10:22,960
His name is Gerald Crane.
He's a biology teacher.

131
00:10:24,400 --> 00:10:27,640
School doesn't let out for hours.
Let's go.

132
00:10:30,680 --> 00:10:33,040
- I'm Kelly.
- Fish.

133
00:10:33,120 --> 00:10:37,120
- Fish?
- That's what I said. Fish.

134
00:10:38,560 --> 00:10:43,120
So where are we? What is this place?

135
00:10:43,200 --> 00:10:47,320
Some people think it's a prison.
Some think it's hell.

136
00:10:47,400 --> 00:10:50,120
I just think it's cold, mostly.

137
00:10:55,400 --> 00:10:57,080
Breakfast.

138
00:10:57,160 --> 00:10:58,520
No.

139
00:11:02,560 --> 00:11:04,520
You gotta let the boss eat first.

140
00:11:05,720 --> 00:11:07,640
People call him Mace.

141
00:11:07,720 --> 00:11:10,080
He's the one in charge?

142
00:11:12,200 --> 00:11:13,400
Okay. Okay.

143
00:11:13,480 --> 00:11:16,800
Get another one. Get another one.
Go on.

144
00:11:50,360 --> 00:11:53,520
Gerald called in one day
and said he wasn't coming in.

145
00:11:53,600 --> 00:11:54,680
- And that's the last I heard of him.
- Let me guess.

146
00:11:54,760 --> 00:11:57,040
- That was three weeks ago?
- Yeah.

147
00:11:57,120 --> 00:11:59,120
So the neighbors said
he up and moved out.

148
00:11:59,200 --> 00:12:01,200
Unis searched the place. Nothing.

149
00:12:01,280 --> 00:12:03,240
So, what can you tell us about Crane?

150
00:12:03,320 --> 00:12:04,480
He was a good teacher.

151
00:12:04,560 --> 00:12:07,000
Focused. And a good father.

152
00:12:07,080 --> 00:12:10,120
He was very protective of his son,
Jonathan.

153
00:12:10,200 --> 00:12:13,840
But he could be quiet too. Somber.

154
00:12:13,920 --> 00:12:16,840
Think it had to do with his wife.
She died six or seven years ago.

155
00:12:16,920 --> 00:12:20,880
- She died? How?
- Car accident.

156
00:12:20,960 --> 00:12:23,560
Did Crane ever talk about
fear or phobias?

157
00:12:23,640 --> 00:12:25,640
Why?

158
00:12:25,720 --> 00:12:28,440
Is someone targeting phobics?

159
00:12:28,520 --> 00:12:29,600
Yeah.

160
00:12:30,880 --> 00:12:33,880
- Killing them?
- Does this mean something to you?

161
00:12:33,960 --> 00:12:36,840
These victims, were they missing
their adrenal glands?

162
00:12:36,920 --> 00:12:38,280
How'd you know that?

163
00:12:43,760 --> 00:12:46,520
This was an academic paper
that Gerald wrote a few months ago.

164
00:12:46,600 --> 00:12:47,680
He asked me to proof it for him.

165
00:12:47,760 --> 00:12:53,040
See, Gerald had a theory that fear
was an evolutionary flaw in humans.

166
00:12:53,120 --> 00:12:57,000
That war, rape, theft, murder,
it was all caused by fear.

167
00:12:57,080 --> 00:12:58,160
He was obsessed with it.

168
00:12:58,240 --> 00:13:01,680
So, Crane killed these people and
took their glands to test a theory?

169
00:13:01,760 --> 00:13:06,240
No. Gerald wasn't trying to prove
he was right about fear.

170
00:13:06,320 --> 00:13:08,600
He was trying to cure himself of it.

171
00:13:08,680 --> 00:13:11,680
Crane's idea of curing fear
was to inoculate himself against it.

172
00:13:11,760 --> 00:13:13,680
- Like a disease?
- Exactly. But in order to do so,

173
00:13:13,760 --> 00:13:17,160
he needed a condensed source
of the hormones that cause fear.

174
00:13:17,240 --> 00:13:19,920
- Phobics.
- Crane's preying on them?

175
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:23,600
Spiking their fear by scaring them
and then killing them in order

176
00:13:23,680 --> 00:13:24,680
to harvest the hormones?

177
00:13:24,760 --> 00:13:26,040
Damn.

178
00:13:26,120 --> 00:13:27,800
How much of this stuff does he need?

179
00:13:27,880 --> 00:13:29,040
What do you mean?

180
00:13:29,120 --> 00:13:31,280
How many more people
is he gonna kill?

181
00:13:31,360 --> 00:13:32,800
Oh. Of course. Good question.

182
00:13:32,880 --> 00:13:36,080
Depends on how scared he is, I guess.
What's he scared of?

183
00:13:36,160 --> 00:13:39,520
In Scottie's phobia support group,
he said he was afraid of failure.

184
00:13:40,560 --> 00:13:42,560
Who isn't?
It's gotta be something else.

185
00:13:44,680 --> 00:13:46,040
- Did you hear?
- Hear what?

186
00:13:46,120 --> 00:13:49,480
That we got a new medical examiner?
Much better than the old one.

187
00:13:49,560 --> 00:13:51,360
And she smells nice.

188
00:13:52,480 --> 00:13:54,480
See, Jim? Competition already.

189
00:13:55,960 --> 00:14:00,120
Look at this. Crane developed
protocols for two inoculations.

190
00:14:00,200 --> 00:14:02,560
Himself and somebody else. Subject B.

191
00:14:02,640 --> 00:14:05,600
I wonder who that is.

192
00:14:37,760 --> 00:14:38,960
Dad.

193
00:14:48,920 --> 00:14:50,520
Dad?

194
00:14:50,600 --> 00:14:52,400
You okay?

195
00:14:52,480 --> 00:14:54,160
I'm glorious.

196
00:14:56,840 --> 00:14:59,080
It's working, Jonathan.

197
00:14:59,160 --> 00:15:00,840
I said it would.

198
00:15:02,560 --> 00:15:05,280
And it's almost your turn.

199
00:15:05,360 --> 00:15:08,000
You will be free of fear forever.

200
00:15:09,160 --> 00:15:10,560
You'll be cured.

201
00:15:12,760 --> 00:15:15,760
Are you ready, Jonathan?
Are you ready, son?

202
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:22,440
- Thank you for having me.
- My pleasure.

203
00:15:22,520 --> 00:15:24,840
- We're friends, right?
- Of course.

204
00:15:24,920 --> 00:15:26,480
Well, let me talk to you as a friend.

205
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:32,240
You wanna have lunch?
Take a walk? I'm happy to.

206
00:15:32,320 --> 00:15:33,720
But a sandwich and a stroll

207
00:15:33,800 --> 00:15:35,480
ain't gonna keep me
from killing Penguin.

208
00:15:35,560 --> 00:15:37,800
That little rat is dead.

209
00:15:39,080 --> 00:15:40,200
So be it.

210
00:15:42,600 --> 00:15:45,840
- Mr. Cobblepot, will this do?
- We will not be serving that.

211
00:15:48,080 --> 00:15:51,880
No, no, no.

212
00:15:51,960 --> 00:15:54,480
I said lose the drapes,
not tie them back.

213
00:15:54,560 --> 00:15:57,120
We're opening in ten hours.

214
00:15:57,200 --> 00:15:59,960
- Sorry.
- Hey, boss.

215
00:16:01,400 --> 00:16:02,400
They're ready.

216
00:16:02,480 --> 00:16:04,800
Still warm from the printer.

217
00:16:08,440 --> 00:16:11,280
Nothing can go wrong tonight, Gabe.

218
00:16:11,360 --> 00:16:14,720
This is more than an opening.
It's my moment.

219
00:16:15,760 --> 00:16:19,280
They're perfect.
Take these to everybody on the list.

220
00:16:22,480 --> 00:16:23,840
But not this one.

221
00:16:25,040 --> 00:16:27,080
This one I wanna deliver in person.

222
00:16:34,480 --> 00:16:37,440
I just want a word. I mean, no harm.

223
00:16:43,400 --> 00:16:45,600
That's close enough.

224
00:16:46,840 --> 00:16:47,840
No harm?

225
00:16:48,960 --> 00:16:51,720
- So you're the boss in here?
- I am.

226
00:16:51,800 --> 00:16:53,480
Why you?

227
00:16:54,600 --> 00:16:56,520
I see a lot of tough guys
around here.

228
00:16:58,240 --> 00:17:03,800
This is the only blade in the place
and I'm holding it.

229
00:17:03,880 --> 00:17:05,720
Fair enough.

230
00:17:12,280 --> 00:17:15,040
- I wanna make a deal with you.
- A deal?

231
00:17:15,120 --> 00:17:17,200
Yeah.

232
00:17:17,280 --> 00:17:21,000
I think I might have skills
that could be useful to you.

233
00:17:21,080 --> 00:17:22,960
Really?

234
00:17:23,040 --> 00:17:25,320
What skills, exactly?

235
00:17:30,520 --> 00:17:33,400
All kinds.

236
00:17:33,480 --> 00:17:36,560
You protect me from these animals
and I'll show you.

237
00:17:36,640 --> 00:17:39,520
You think you're worth protecting?

238
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:43,560
You have no idea.

239
00:18:44,360 --> 00:18:47,560
- Can I help you?
- I don't think so. Can you?

240
00:18:50,200 --> 00:18:51,640
What do you want?

241
00:18:51,720 --> 00:18:53,360
What I want, the poor have,

242
00:18:53,440 --> 00:18:55,120
the rich need,
and if you eat it you'll die.

243
00:18:56,600 --> 00:18:59,240
Is this...?
Are you asking me a riddle?

244
00:18:59,320 --> 00:19:01,320
- Do you like riddles?
- No.

245
00:19:01,400 --> 00:19:03,000
So, do you give up?

246
00:19:04,800 --> 00:19:05,800
- Friend, look...
- Nothing.

247
00:19:05,880 --> 00:19:06,920
The answer is nothing.

248
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:09,200
The poor have it,
the rich need it and if you eat it...

249
00:19:09,280 --> 00:19:14,120
- Who are you?
- Edward Nygma.

250
00:19:14,200 --> 00:19:15,840
I know who you are.

251
00:19:18,080 --> 00:19:20,560
Then you know
that you're standing too close.

252
00:19:26,640 --> 00:19:28,640
Did you know male emperor
penguins keep their eggs warm

